---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";
---

<Layout
  title="AtlasNXT Case Study | Adam McKenna | Full Stack Developer"
  description="Atlas NXT is a duty-of-care platform used by organisations including the BBC, UN and FCDO."
>
  <header
    class="col-start-5 w-full col-span-4 justify-center grid gap-2 md:gap-4"
  >
    <a
      class="mb-4 md:mb-0 text-xs md:text-base flex items-center gap-2 no-underline"
      href="/"
    >
      <img class="w-4 md:w-7" src="./icons/arrow.svg" />
      Back to home
    </a>
    <h2 class="text-base md:text-lg text-primary-dark -mb-1">case study</h2>

    <h1 class="text-4xl font-semibold lg:text-5xl">AtlasNXT</h1>

    <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-3 opacity-75">
      <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-1.5">
        <div
          class="rounded bg-support text-background font-normal py-1 px-2 text-xs transition-all"
        >
          UX/UI
        </div>
        <div
          class="rounded bg-support text-background font-normal py-1 px-2 text-xs transition-all"
        >
          Frontend
        </div>
        <div
          class="rounded bg-support text-background font-normal py-1 px-2 text-xs transition-all"
        >
          Backend
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-1.5">
        <div
          class="rounded bg-secondary text-background font-normal py-1 px-2 text-xs transition-all"
        >
          Elixir & Phoenix
        </div>
        <div
          class="rounded bg-secondary text-background font-normal py-1 px-2 text-xs transition-all"
        >
          JavaScript
        </div>
        <div
          class="rounded bg-secondary text-background font-normal py-1 px-2 text-xs transition-all"
        >
          HTML
        </div>
        <div
          class="rounded bg-secondary text-background font-normal py-1 px-2 text-xs transition-all"
        >
          Tailwind
        </div>
        <div
          class="rounded bg-secondary text-background font-normal py-1 px-2 text-xs transition-all"
        >
          Mapbox
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p class="text-sm/6 sm:text-base/7">
      <span class="font-semibold"
        ><a href="https://atlasnxt.com/" target="_blank">AtlasNXT</a> is a duty-of-care
        platform used by organisations including the BBC, UN and FCDO.</span
      >
    </p>

    <img
      class="col-span-8 col-start-3 my-6"
      src="./atlas-nxt-mockup.png"
      alt="AtlasNXT application mockup"
    />

    <section class="grid gap-2 col-span-6 col-start-4">
      <p class="text-sm/6 sm:text-base/7">
        <strong
          >AtlasNXT is a SaaS duty-of-care platform developed by Track24</strong
        > to help organisations monitor and protect their staff in
        <strong>high-risk environments</strong>, such as conflict zones or
        politically unstable regions. The platform is two-fold:
        <strong>a real-time map interface for operators</strong>, and
        <strong>a field app / Garmin InReach device</strong> used by employees who
        can be alerted to dangers and tracked to ensure they stay safe.
      </p>

      <h2
        class="font-semibold mt-3 flex flex-wrap sm:text-xl sm:mt-4 lg:text-1xl"
      >
        Context &amp; Problem
      </h2>

      <p class="text-sm/6 sm:text-base/7">
        When I joined Track24 at the end of 2024, AtlasNXT was already
        <strong>live and functional</strong>. The Elixir Phoenix application had
        been built by a <strong
          >rotating door of contractors working largely in silo</strong
        >. While the platform worked functionally, the frontend experience
        lagged behind:
      </p>

      <ul class="list-disc ml-4">
        <li class="text-sm/6 sm:text-base/7">
          <strong>UI consistency was extremely poor</strong>, with many elements
          minimally designed or left with browser defaults.
        </li>
        <li class="text-sm/6 sm:text-base/7">
          <strong>User flows felt fragmented</strong>.
        </li>
        <li class="text-sm/6 sm:text-base/7">
          <strong>Little visual feedback, animation, or polish</strong>.
        </li>
        <li class="text-sm/6 sm:text-base/7">
          The interface <strong>did not inspire confidence</strong> proportional
          to the seriousness of the product’s use cases.
        </li>
        <li class="text-sm/6 sm:text-base/7">
          The platform met baseline requirements but offered
          <strong>no customer delight</strong>.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <p class="text-sm/6 sm:text-base/7">
        Given AtlasNXT’s use in <strong>genuinely high-stakes situations</strong
        >, these issues directly affected <strong
          >usability, trust, and operator efficiency</strong
        >, and made the product <strong>harder to market and sell</strong>.
      </p>

      <h2
        class="font-semibold mt-3 flex flex-wrap sm:text-xl sm:mt-4 lg:text-1xl"
      >
        My Role
      </h2>

      <p class="text-sm/6 sm:text-base/7">
        I joined as the de facto
        <strong>Lead Frontend Engineer</strong>, with ownership over
        <strong>user experience and frontend architecture</strong>. I wasn’t
        hired to ship major new features initially, but to
        <strong>raise the quality bar across the application</strong> and transform
        a purely functional interface into one that felt
        <strong>deliberate, trustworthy, and calm under pressure</strong>.
      </p>

      <img
        src="./atlas-nxt-animation.gif"
        class="mt-2"
        alt="AtlasNXT UI animation"
        loading="lazy"
        decoding="async"
      />
      <p class="text-philippine-grey text-xs font-light mt-[1px]">
        Subtle UI animations introduced across the platform.
      </p>

      <h2
        class="font-semibold mt-3 flex flex-wrap sm:text-xl sm:mt-4 lg:text-1xl"
      >
        Approach
      </h2>

      <p class="text-sm/6 sm:text-base/7">
        Rather than a single large redesign, my first six months focused on
        <strong>systematic, incremental improvements</strong> across the entire UI:
      </p>

      <ul class="list-disc ml-4">
        <li class="text-sm/6 sm:text-base/7">
          Worked closely with the in-house product designer to
          <strong>identify and prioritise UX improvements</strong>.
        </li>
        <li class="text-sm/6 sm:text-base/7">
          <strong>Documented and tracked UX issues</strong> extensively in Linear.
        </li>
        <li class="text-sm/6 sm:text-base/7">
          Audited the application to surface
          <strong>repeated UX pain points and inconsistencies</strong>.
        </li>
        <li class="text-sm/6 sm:text-base/7">
          <strong
            >Standardised layouts, typography, and interaction patterns</strong
          > via a Figma design system.
        </li>
        <li class="text-sm/6 sm:text-base/7">
          Introduced subtle animations to
          <strong>increase customer delight and saleability</strong>.
        </li>
        <li class="text-sm/6 sm:text-base/7">
          <strong>Overhauled high-visibility views</strong> such as the login experience.
        </li>
        <li class="text-sm/6 sm:text-base/7">
          Implemented <strong>accessibility best practices</strong>: focus
          states, labelling, tab ordering, empty/loading/error states.
        </li>
        <li class="text-sm/6 sm:text-base/7">
          Reduced visual noise in
          <strong>critical workflows where speed and clarity matter most</strong
          >.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <img
        src="./atlas-nxt-mockup-figma.png"
        class="mt-2"
        alt="AtlasNXT Figma design system"
        loading="lazy"
        decoding="async"
      />
      <p class="text-philippine-grey text-xs font-light mt-[1px]">
        Figma design system.
      </p>

      <h2
        class="font-semibold mt-3 flex flex-wrap sm:text-xl sm:mt-4 lg:text-1xl"
      >
        Key Contributions
      </h2>

      <ul class="list-disc ml-4">
        <li class="text-sm/6 sm:text-base/7">
          <strong
            >Established a consistent visual and interaction language</strong
          > across the application.
        </li>
        <li class="text-sm/6 sm:text-base/7">
          Refactored ad-hoc UI into
          <strong>reusable, predictable Phoenix components</strong>.
        </li>
        <li class="text-sm/6 sm:text-base/7">
          <strong>Improved operator confidence and delight</strong> through usability
          and polish.
        </li>
        <li class="text-sm/6 sm:text-base/7">
          <strong>Elevated perceived product quality</strong> without disrupting
          workflows.
        </li>
        <li class="text-sm/6 sm:text-base/7">
          <strong>Improved accessibility compliance</strong>, a key requirement
          for government contracts.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <img
        src="./atlas-nxt-login-before-after.png"
        class="mt-2"
        alt="AtlasNXT login page before and after re-design"
        loading="lazy"
        decoding="async"
      />
      <p class="text-philippine-grey text-xs font-light mt-[1px]">
        Login page before and after re-design.
      </p>

      <h2
        class="font-semibold mt-3 flex flex-wrap sm:text-xl sm:mt-4 lg:text-1xl"
      >
        Outcome
      </h2>

      <p class="text-sm/6 sm:text-base/7">
        While much of the work was subtle, the
        <strong>cumulative effect was significant</strong>. AtlasNXT evolved
        from feeling like an internal tool into a
        <strong>polished, production-grade platform</strong> suitable for enterprise
        and government clients.
      </p>

      <p class="text-sm/6 sm:text-base/7">
        The improved frontend foundation made
        <strong>subsequent feature development faster and safer</strong>,
        supported by a coherent UI system and reusable components.
      </p>

      <p class="text-sm/6 sm:text-base/7">
        These changes translated into
        <strong>real business impact</strong>, with clients and stakeholders
        explicitly complimenting the animations and redesigned login experience.
      </p>

      <img
        src="./atlas-nxt-animation-heatmap.gif"
        class="mt-2"
        alt="AtlasNXT UI heatmap animation"
        loading="lazy"
        decoding="async"
      />
      <p class="text-philippine-grey text-xs font-light mt-[1px]">
        Heatmap animation.
      </p>

      <h2
        class="font-semibold mt-3 flex flex-wrap sm:text-xl sm:mt-4 lg:text-1xl"
      >
        Reflection
      </h2>

      <p class="text-sm/6 sm:text-base/7">
        This project reinforced the value of
        <strong>quality over quantity</strong>. By focusing on consistency,
        usability, and polish — and extrapolating those improvements across the
        system — AtlasNXT became
        <strong>more trustworthy, calmer, and more delightful</strong> for both existing
        and future customers.
      </p>
    </section>
  </header>
</Layout>
